<article>
    <h1>His&#xAD;tory ga&#xAD;lore in the west</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>While per­haps not the first mu­seum one would think of for a fam­ily out­ing, the iconic For­mer Ford Fac­tory (right, 351 Up­per Bukit Timah Road) in all its Art Decor glory makes for an in­for­ma­tive walk down wartime mem­ory lane.</p>
    <p>With chil­dren in tow, aim to cover the com­pre­hen­sive ex­hi­bi­tion in per­haps two or more vis­its.</p>
    <p>I ex­plained ex­hibits and bits that ap­pealed to Elna’s young mind while read­ing the con­cise de­scrip­tions on the Bri­tish sur­ren­der and the Ja­panese Oc­cu­pa­tion of Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>Have cardi­gans on hand for ev­ery­one as it can get quite cold in the mu­seum. Ad­mis­sion is free for Sin­ga­pore­ans and per­ma­nent res­i­dents.</p>
    <p>Con­tin­u­ing the World War II tra­jec­tory, skip Bukit Timah Na­ture Re­serve and head to the much smaller but equally lush Bukit Ba­tok Na­ture Park (along Bukit Ba­tok East Av­enue 2 and Bukit Ba­tok East Av­enue 6) that is home to a quarry lake and a World War II me­mo­rial.</p>
    <p>All that is left to­day are the road and stairs built by Aus­tralian pris­on­ers of war, but there is plenty of wildlife and the trails are hilly although still doable with a light­weight stroller.</p>
    <p>From the me­mo­rial, it is about a 20-minute walk to Beauty World</p>
    <p>Food Cen­tre. Score seats at the edge of the build­ing for an al­fresco rooftop din­ner, with a sun­set view thrown in if you are lucky.</p>

